Explore how driving distance is related to demographic variables

# Calculate total number of families and children in grades 1-5 per block
data$total_families <- data$families_w_under18_abovepov + data$families_w_under18_belowpov
data$total_grade_1_5 <- data$grade_1_5_white + data$grade_1_5_two + data$grade_1_5_other +
                        data$grade_1_5_Haw_PI + data$grade_1_5_asian + data$grade_1_5_Am_ind +
                        data$grade_1_5_black + data$grade_1_5_Hisp

There are blocks that have no families or elementary school-aged children. Remove these blocks from the dataset.

data_w_kids <- data[data$total_grade_1_5 > 0,]
# Calculate % of families in poverty
data_w_kids$pct_families_belowpov <- data_w_kids$families_w_under18_belowpov/data_w_kids$total_families

# Calculate % of children by race
data_w_kids$pct_white <- data_w_kids$grade_1_5_white/data_w_kids$total_grade_1_5
data_w_kids$pct_black <- data_w_kids$grade_1_5_black/data_w_kids$total_grade_1_5
data_w_kids$pct_hisp <- data_w_kids$grade_1_5_Hisp/data_w_kids$total_grade_1_5
data_w_kids$pct_other <- (data_w_kids$grade_1_5_Am_ind + data_w_kids$grade_1_5_asian + data_w_kids$grade_1_5_two + data_w_kids$grade_1_5_other)/data_w_kids$total_grade_1_5  # collapse the smaller racial categories into one

Explore relationship between poverty levels and distance to school

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_families_belowpov, y=dis_rating_above_6, color=charter)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(. ~ charter)

The relationship seems stronger if you filter out charter schools.

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=charter, y=dis_rating_above_6)) + geom_boxplot()

More variation in distance to a charter school.

Explore relationship between school distance and race

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_white, y=dis_rating_above_6, color=charter)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(. ~ charter)

Few white children have to travel more than 1 mile to get to a good school.

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_black, y=dis_rating_above_6, color=charter)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(. ~ charter)

More variability in distance among blocks with many black children compared to white children.

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_hisp, y=dis_rating_above_6, color=charter)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(. ~ charter)

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_other, y=dis_rating_above_6, color=charter)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(. ~ charter)

Explore relationship between race and poverty

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_white, y=pct_families_belowpov)) + geom_point() 

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_black, y=pct_families_belowpov)) + geom_point() 

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_hisp, y=pct_families_belowpov)) + geom_point() 

ggplot(data_w_kids, aes(x=pct_other, y=pct_families_belowpov)) + geom_point()

Definitely seems to be a relationship between race and poverty.

Story seems to be that poorer, minority kids tend to live farther than their wealthier, white peers do from good schools.

Prep Data for Plotting:

final <- data_w_kids[,c("id", "geography", "dis_rating_above_6", "school_name", "pct_families_belowpov", "total_grade_1_5", 
                        "pct_white", "pct_black", "pct_hisp", "pct_other")]

# Add an indicator for blocks where the share of families in poverty exceeds the district-wide poverty rate (18.6%)
final$high_poverty <- 0
final$high_poverty[final$pct_families_belowpov > 0.186] <- 1

write.csv(final, "data_for_plot.csv", row.names = FALSE)
